args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that the subject category or collection includes the object as an example member or instance (often introduced by phrases like 'such as').
args.justification: The relation connects a general category ('new tissues and structures') to a specific instance ('butterfly wings') marked by the logical marker 'such as', which denotes example membership rather than physical part-of composition.

args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that a life cycle or process includes the object as one of its stages or phases.
args.justification: The subject 'butterfly life cycle' is a process that includes 'pupa stage' as a defined phase, so a general process-to-stage predicate ('has_stage') captures this semantics cleanly.

The relation expresses that a specific instance (butterfly wings) belongs to or exemplifies a broader category of entities (new tissues and structures), which is best modeled as a membership/example-type relation rather than strict physical composition.
The link between a life cycle and one of its stages is a canonical example of a process-to-stage (phase) relation, so it fits a 'process_stage_relation' class.
The semantics is that of set/category membership or example association, not physical or material composition; this fits better under a broad ASSOCIATION group than COMPOSITION.
Stages of a life cycle are temporally ordered phases of a process; the core dimension of this relation is temporal progression within a process, so TEMPORALITY is the most suitable broad group.
